Written e[bold]vidence [bold]submitted by the[bold] Legal Aid Practitioners Group (LAPG) [bold](LAI 0073)[bold]T
[normal]he Committee seeks evidence from anyone with an interest in the human rights issues raised by the following proposals in particular:
[normal]1. Legal Aid Practitioner Group is a membership body for organisations (private practice and not-for-profit) with legal aid contracts with the Legal Aid Agency. Our members are based throughout England and Wales and cover all areas of law.
[normal] We meet r
[normal]egularly with the Ministry of Justice and Legal Aid Agency on policy and operational issues affecting our members.
[normal]Summary[bold]2. It is LAPG’s view that these proposals wholly undermine the fundamental common law right of access to the court for all. The chang
[normal]es are a direct attack on the rule of law and will have an immediate adverse impact not only on vulnerable client groups, but also on all clients seeking legal advice for a range of civil problems. In summary we consider that
[normal]3. 
[normal]These proposals must not be rushed through with little Parliamentary scrutiny. 
[normal]We are concerned that these proposals will 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Residence test[bold] - [bold]The [bold]proposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid claimants, so as to limit legal aid to those with a “strong connection” with the UK[bold]4. 
[normal]In our response
[normal] to the Transforming Legal Aid Consultation LAPG took the view that this proposal is unlawful, unjust, impractical
[normal], discriminatory
[normal] and unnecessary.
[normal]  [bold]Despite the amendments made to the proposal we remain of this view.
[normal] 
[normal]There are two limbs to the proposal: to
[normal] be lawfully resident in the UK, crown dependencies or overseas territories 
[normal]and[bold] to have resided lawfully in these places for
[normal] a ‘continuous period’
[normal] 
[normal]of 
[normal]12 months. 
[normal]5. We are aware that the JCHR has limited resources and that others have dealt with issues of 
[normal]legality e.g. Dr Nick Armstrong and Paul Bowen QC. We endorse their responses and in particular Dr Nick Armstrong’s analysis of the very limited nature of the concessions made by the Government (
[normal]para
[normal] 6 onwards). We would also highlight Treasury Counsel’s r
[normal]esponse to the original consultation and their concerns about the residence test.
[normal]6. It is important to emphasise that 
[normal]all clients[bold] will need to meet the test. The scale of the task is immense both for practitioners and for the Legal Aid Agency in checking that the test is met. 
[normal]In 2012-13 alone there were:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal](a) 
[normal]590
[normal],
[normal]410 Civil Legal Help funded acts of assistance; 
[normal](b) 
[normal]139,083 authoris
[normal]ed acts of certificated representation.
[normal]This means that if current take-up continues, 729,493 people will have to meet the test, and prove that they do so before legal aid can be provided. 
[normal]It is our view that removing legal aid from people who do not meet 
[normal]the residence test will result in some of the neediest and most vulnerable people being placed at immediate risk of harm or even death. This is not acceptable in a democratic and civilised society, with a reputation for upholding fundamental principles of 
[normal]access to justice. Even those who would meet the residence test will be excluded for the reasons we set out below.
[normal]7. We are a practitioner organisation and our members deliver legal aid services on the ground to clients day in, day out. We would therefore
[normal] like to draw attention to the practical effect of this proposal on clients and access to justice. Clients seeking legal advice on areas which remain within scope of LASPOA are, in the main, due to the refocusing of legal aid on priority areas, those seeki
[normal]ng advice regarding protection of the person or their home. The eligible client group is therefore by definition more vulnerable than previously. Already there have been additional burdensome requirements placed on clients to produce evidence to prove thei
[normal]r eligibility and that their case falls within the scope of the new legal aid scheme. The more hurdles put in the path of vulnerable clients, the harder it is to reach the point where any advice is accessible and offered. Legal Action Group has highlighted
[normal] the drop in the number of people obtaining advice – the reduction is far greater than the effect of LASPOA:  
[normal]http://www.lag.org.uk/policy-campaigns/legal-aid-secret-service.
[normal]aspx
[normal]8. Clients who are vulnerable and in the stressful situations that necessitate advice can only obtain that advice at present if they:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9. P
[normal]eople seeking legal advice
[normal] under the legal aid scheme are invariably vulnerable and are often facing a time of great stress. Already the number of organisations offering a legal aid service has declined drastically and it is now extremely difficult for clients to find the advice th
[normal]ey need from someone who is skilled, able and willing to take on the case. Even if they do find a practitioner who is willing to assist, not only do they
[normal] have to overcome the financial evidence hurdle
[normal], but if the residence test is introduced, clients will 
[normal]also have to meet a further documentary evidence threshold for even the most basic legal advice. 
[normal]Many cli
[normal]ents will struggle (and fail) to provide documentary evidence of all 
[normal]elements
[normal] of the various tests to access legal advice
[normal]. 
[normal]This will leave them without
[normal] the protection they need. Many will be homeless or placed at risk of violence or abuse as a result.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10. We met with the 
[normal]MoJ
[normal] to discuss what documentary evidence was being proposed by the Ministry to meet the test. On the ‘lawful residence’ limb of the te
[normal]st it was proposed that the following evidence might be sufficient – a valid passport or a valid visa. On the ‘continuous period of 1 year’ limb it was suggested that evidence might include audited accounts from the person’s business, a letter from their e
[normal]mployer, letters from their children’s school etc. There was a helpful discussion however the outcome was that the test would not be met by many of the most vulnerable groups such as those in crisis, those fleeing violence, the disabled and mentally ill. T
[normal]hese groups are highly unlikely to have the documentary evidence to meet the test and even if they are in fact eligible, would fail because of the evidence requirement.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1
[normal]1
[normal]. Lawful residence. The problems in proving this will include the following:
[normal]12. Lawfully Resident for One Year. People will also have to prove that they have been in the country for a continuous period of year (subject to a permitted 30 day absence). How will people 
[normal]who are in crisis accommodation, who have fled their home, who are homeless be able to prove this? These are factors which will be hurdles:-
[normal]13
[normal].
[normal] In reality, many of the clients our members advise have chaotic lives. They do not bring with them organised lever arch files of bank statements, passports, visas, letters fr
[normal]om GPs or schools. Take a person who has been discharged from psychiatric hospital without suitable housing. S/he is unlikely to have evidence to meet the residence test. Clients with dementia, learning disabilities, people who are street homeless etc
[normal].
[normal] who need advice will not be able to produce the necessary proof. Everyone will be affected by the test because everyone will have to meet it to qualify for legal aid.
[normal] 
[normal]14. The Government’s purported concessions on excluding the most vulnerable from the re
[normal]sidence test will not cure the problem. In particular, the removal of ‘detention’ cases will not, on the current proposals, apply for example to people lacking mental capacity who are de facto detained in care homes, hospitals or in their own homes, or who
[normal] are being abused or neglected. If ‘detention’ cases only apply to, for example, persons who are being detained under the Mental Health Act, then this still leaves a whole host of other clients who are in a similar position (but not necessarily formally ‘d
[normal]etained’) without any access to legal advice or protection.
