[normal]. We support the evidence submitted by the Association of Prison Lawyers. 
[normal]Our main concerns are
[normal] that
[normal]:
[normal]W
[normal]ithout entering into a detailed analysis of relevant case
[normal] 
[normal]law (which others are better placed to do so),
[normal] simply because a person has been imprisoned for a crime does not mean that all rights should be denied to them
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Judicial review:[bold] The proposal that providers of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid fo[bold]r work done on the case if the Court grants permission for the application to proceed[bold]1
[normal]8
[normal]. As with so
[normal] many of these proposals the Government does not seem to have given proper consideration or thought through the true cost of its proposals and any perverse 
[normal]incentives created. The original responses to the TLA Consultation highlighted these and they remain. 
[normal]The 
[normal]MoJ’s
[normal] response to the 16,000 consultations has been to propose that where a 
[normal]judicial review 
[normal]case has been issued and settles without permission having
[normal] been granted, the LAA 
[normal]may
[normal] nevertheless pay the lawyers provided there is a good reason why the defendant has not been ordered to pay
[normal] costs
[normal].
[normal]1
[normal]9
[normal]. It is essential to highlight the effect on those seeking redress through judicial review - the system is of cou
[normal]rse designed for individuals to enforce rights, and not to ensure a good income for lawyers. However rights do not exist in a vacuum. We would highlight one practical issue of all of the recent legal aid cuts – the inability of legal aid practitioners to c
[normal]arry out an ever increasing amount of work unpaid or ‘at risk’. Already legal aid fees are below what is understood to be ‘the market rate’ (for example for much civil legal aid the rates are those set in 1994, less the 10% cut imposed in October 2011) but
[normal] that does not explain the real cost of carrying out legal aid work. There is already considerable unpaid time which people will refer to in this response e
[normal].
[normal]g.
[normal] 
[normal]checking financial eligibility, helping clients obtain evidence of domestic violence, filling in
[normal] the exceptional funding form, but also the unremitting complexity of the revised legal aid system means that it would be quite easy to work a ten hour day and only produce five definite chargeable hours which might be paid.
[normal]20
[normal]. As a membership organisation we know the pressures our members are under and we can confirm that the line has been reached where no further cuts to even the low levels of funding can be 
[normal]sustained. The rest of the work carried out by firms does not suppor
[normal]t cross-subsidisation of unpaid or at risk legal aid work. The ‘concession’ of a discretionary payment if the case settles pre permission but costs are not paid by the opponent will not help to ensure that practitioners can carry out legal aid work. This i
[normal]s because such work cannot reach that stage without guarantees of some payment, even at low legal aid rates.
[normal]21. It is important to explain that judicial review cases, unlike other types of litigation, involve extensive work in the early stages to prepare 
[normal]the case for issue. Other litigation can start with a simple application form and short statement, and the costs are very low. This is not the case for most judicial reviews, because what is required in bringing proceedings is a detailed document setting o
[normal]ut the legal grounds of challenge, supported by full evidence. The duty to the Court to make full disclosure from the start of the case means that the work is very heavy and labour intensive in the early stages of the case. All of this work will be at risk
[normal] if the proposal proceeds, and the result will be that practitioners simply will not take the risk of either not being granted permission (because for example, a third party takes some action outside the practitioner’s control rendering the proceedings aca
[normal]demic) or not receiving the discretionary payment from the Legal Aid Agency.
[normal]22. There is a simple solution. The LAA is legally and contractually responsible for considering legal aid applications for judicial review, applying the relevant Merits Regulatio
[normal]ns and criteria, and deciding which cases warrant public funding to take forward. Only meritorious cases should succeed. Moreover the Judge, on considering permission, and in refusing permission in those cases could certify that the case was ‘wholly withou
[normal]t merit’ and recommend that the practitioner’s costs should not be paid. We do not think that political rhetoric should overturn this procedure.
[normal]23. To allow the LAA to have the discretion on payment, when the exceptional funding cases have been so limited
[normal], would be unlikely to persuade practitioners to take the risk. Valid cases, particularly those which are complex and therefore cost more initially to bring to permission, will simply not be brought at all. The Public Law Project has carried out considerab
[normal]le work on Judicial Review trends and we urge the Committee to consider their findings. 
[normal]24. We do urge the Committee to consider fully the importance of judicial review as a way for ordinary citizens (some of whose dependence on the state for assistance m
[normal]eans that they would be severely affected by this proposal) to challenge large organisations and that that is important constitutionally. It is also of fundamental importance to ensure that the laws of the country apply to everyone.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The proposal that [bold]lega[bold]l aid should be removed for all cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of success.[bold]25.
[normal] 
[normal]Borderline cases are high priority but very rare cases including cases holding the state to account, public interest cases and cases concernin
[normal]g housing, and 
[normal]including asylum
[normal].
[normal]26.
[normal] 
[normal]It may not be possible to evaluate the chances of obtaining a successful outcome, because there is a dispute about the facts, the law or expert evidence.  These cases are not ones where the prospects of success are less than 50% or po
[normal]or
[normal] rather that
[normal] t
[normal]he prospects 
[normal]cannot[bold] be assessed 
[normal]because 
[normal]the court 
[normal]m
[normal]ust interpret the law, decide on the disputed facts 
[normal]or expert evidence
[normal].
[normal] However much work is done there is no answer available in these circumstances and the matter needs to go before a judge.
[normal]27. 
[normal]The current merits regulations provide that borderline cases can be funded by legal aid because of their importance, either to the
[normal] individual or constitutionally because they are about holding the state to account.
[normal] We remain of the view that they should continue to be funded, because of those reasons
[normal].
[normal] If there is any doubt about the merit of the cases, then the Legal Aid Agency can (
[normal]as it does at present) scrutinise the application for public funding particularly carefully.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction of these proposals.[bold]2
[normal]8
[normal]. The proposals to introduce these major constitutional changes by means of secondary legislation with very limited Parliamenta
[normal]ry scrutiny is deeply worrying. 
[normal]29. We also regret that the Minister has declined to delay implementation of the reforms pending the reporting by the 
[normal]Joint 
[normal]Committee on the Human Rights implications of the proposals. 
[normal]30. Finally it is also of extreme con
[normal]cern that these proposed changes come so quickly after the detailed Parliamentary debates on LASPOA and after commitments to, for example, retaining
[normal] legal aid for judicial review 
[normal]were made and reconfirmed by the Government.  
[normal]These proposals appear to overt
[normal]urn such assurances.
